This could change based on the epidemiological situation. If any changes occur, you will be informed in advance on this page.

It is also important to monitor the latest information given by your school. Specifically the information from the academic department related to the date and form of the exams and the hygienic regulations surrounding them. Also, check the school website.

At the present time, students are preparing for their exams through distance education, since in-person education is not allowed. This ban also applies to practical education, with the exception of medical specializations who will continue in practical education.

We are all going through a difficult time right now, if you need any psychological help or tips on how to cope with stress, look in the section on Stress and handling the impact of the pandemic.

3b.title: eNeschopenka
3b.content:
Rules and recommendations

eNeschopenka is a sick leave (reporting incapacity to work) for the employer and the social security administration, which is issued electronically by a doctor.

The purpose of the eNeschopenka is to simplify the transfer of information, as it connects electronically three different entities — doctors, employers and the Czech Social Security Administration (ČSSZ).

eNeschopenka refers to the temporary incapacity to work. In practice, it means that the employee does not have to carry physical paper documents anywhere — it can be handled online remotely, from home and without the risk of getting infected. The employee will receive a certificate of incapacity to work which can be useful in the case of an inspection of the competent authorities.

3c.title: Proms
3c.content:
Rules and recommendations

We do know that your prom is an event you look forward to during your entire study time. Unfortunately, due to the recent epidemic situation it isn't possible to carry out any mass event now.

Indoor events are permitted indeed - but only up to 10 persons maximum and under maintaining other hygienic precautions.

Thus, proms as such aren't forbidden, rather restricted to the number of participants stated above. Any changes of this measure will depend on the epidemic situation at the time when your prom is supposed to take place.

3d.title: Entrance exams
3d.content:
Rules and recommendations

At the moment, it is assumed that the entrance exams will take place the normal way, i.e. in the personal presence of students.

This may change as the epidemiological situation develops /keeps developing. You will be informed about the change on time on this website.

You should also keep track of the information provided by the school you are applying to. Especially information from the student department, specifically on the dates, form of entrance exams and hygienic measures.

We are all going through difficult times now. If you need psychological help or advice on coping with stress, look into the Stress and Pandemic Impact Management

3e.title: Mental hygiene of frontline workers
3e.content:
Recommendations

The basic recommendations (in Czech) for maintaining mental health during a pandemic were issued by the Association of Clinical Psychologists of the Czech Republic. 

Special crisis lines have also been set up for paramedics and other front-line workers:

  • COLLEGIAL SUPPORT LINE for healthcare workers: 607 400 591, 720 219 618
  • SOCIAL CLINICS: PSYCHOLOGICAL ASSISTANCE FOR ASSISTING PROFESSIONS (doctors, health professionals, social workers, teachers, hygienists, firefighters, and police officers, etc.): 733 644 268 or online: https://www.socialniklinika.cz
  • Support and supervision #dělámcomůžu: 116 123

3f.title: Wage compensation
3f.content:
The wage compensation is regulated in the Labor Code. The most important areas related to the wage compensation are:

Quarantine ordered to an employee

Employees, who have been quarantined, are entitled to a wage compensation of 60% of their average earnings during the first 14 days. From the 15th calendar day, the sickness insurance benefit starts.

Forced closure of an establishment in connection with the measures taken by the public authorities

This situation typically applies to cases when the employer has to reduce or close down operations according to the announced measures. In such a case, the employer is obliged to pay employees 100% of the average earnings.

The absence of a substantial part of employees in the workplace

If a significant proportion of the employees is absent from work as a result of measures related to the coronavirus pandemic (e.g. employees from abroad cannot get to work), and the employer is unable to assign work to them, employees are entitled to 100% of their average earnings.

Downtime

Downtime is when the employer cannot assign work to employees due to a temporary defect or other operational causes which are not caused by the employer. Typically, this may be a reduction in the supplies of materials due to the crisis. In this case, the employee is entitled to a salary of 80% of their average earnings.

Partial unemployment

If the employer is unable to assign work due to a temporary restriction of the sales of their products or a reduction in the demand for the services they provide (which are a result of Covid-19), the employee is entitled to a wage compensation of 100%. Unless otherwise agreed in an internal regulation or with a trade union, wage compensation can be at least 60% of average earnings.

3g.title: Grief and loss
3g.content:
Recommendation

Coping with the grief of losing a loved one during the pandemic can be especially challenging. The restrictions of face-to-face meetings do not allow you to meet friends and family for mutual support.

If you have lost a loved one, feelings of sadness are a completely natural reaction to a traumatic event.

Common reactions to a traumatic event may include:

  • Shock
  • Denial
  • Anxiety
  • Sadness
  • Anger
  • Sleeping problems
  • Loss of appetite 

People cope with loss in different ways, the following steps can help you:

  • Contact other loved ones: call or write to your friends or family. Share memories or photos that remind you of your loved one with email and video calls or social media with family and friends.
  • Engage in activities that remind you of a loved one: e.g. preparing their favourite food, dedicate memory to your loved one.
  • If necessary, do not be afraid to contact the helplines: for a list of helplines, see Stress and handling the impacts of the pandemic> Helplines.  
  • Seek spiritual support from church organizations:

During the COVID-19 pandemic, the family and close friends of a person who died on COVID-19 may experience stigmatization from others. If you feel misunderstood, rejected by people around you, this probably arises from a lack of awareness of these people about the pandemic. Try to explain the situation to these people, and if you don't feel like it, you should avoid them.

Teenagers coping with loss

Teenagers can cope with loss in different ways than adults. Reactions to loss include, for example, significant sleep disturbance,  trying to isolate from family, irritability, frustration, clinging to technology (spending time on social networks, playing games, etc.)

Parents should try to talk about the loss, and express their support. If necessary, adolescents can contact helplines dedicated to them, a list of which can be found in the Stress and handling the impacts of the pandemic> Helplines.

Children coping with a loss

Children may cope with grief in different ways than adults. It can be especially difficult for some children to understand and cope with the loss of a loved one. Sometimes children seem sad and talk about missing the person. Other times, they play and communicate and do their usual activities without showing signs of longing.

If a child is sad, you can help them by:

  • Discussing the situation with them and trying to understand their perception of the event.
  • If the child has questions, try to answer them according to their age.
  • Try to keep your child's daily routine as usual as possible.
  • Spend time with your child reading, drawing, or other activities they enjoy.

If you feel that your child needs further help (especially if there are significant changes in their behaviour), you can contact one of the helplines dedicated to parents in Stress and handling the impacts of the pandemic> Helplines. Or contact a paediatrician.

3h.title: Contact with an infected person
3h.content:
Risky encounter

A risky encounter means that a healthy person met with someone who tested positive for COVID-19.

Signs of a risky encounter

Direct physical contact (e. g. a handshake, a kiss or a hug) or contact for 15 minutes or more with a distance of less than 2 meters.

Said contact took place. What's next?

If you've had a risky encounter with someone who is infected you should quarantine.

Do not wait for the regional hygiene station to call you. Please go into voluntary quarantine. If you were infected this will prevent further transmissions of the disease. Inform your GP about the risky encounter by phone. They will give you a request form for an RT-PCR test on COVID-19.

3i.title: Job interviews
3i.content:
Rules and recommendations

If it is possible, currently all activities are recommended to be carried out using online platforms (MS Teams, Skype, Zoom, etc.). This also applies to job interviews. There are no special rules or recommendations for the job interviews, the way how the interview is conducted depends on each employer.

3j.title: Self-reporting
3j.content:
Recommendations

If the result of your test is positive, then the text message will also include the code. You use that to gain access to the self-reporting form.

Completing this form will facilitate the work of trace call centres and speed up the flow of information. Self-reporting forms are processed preferentially by regional hygienic stations.

The contacts will be asked to quarantine and thus significantly prevent the further spread of COVID-19.

Please self-report. It will help reduce the spread of the disease. Thank you.

3k.title: Statistical data
3k.content:
Overview of the current situation in the Czech Republic

Detailed overview of the data and analyses.

3l.title: eRouška / eFaceMask
3l.content:
What is the eRouška app for?

The eRouška (meaning eFaceMask) application was created by the “Smart Quarantine” team as one of the tools to get the COVID-19 illness under control and prevent community spread.

How does it work?

The app collects anonymous data about encounters with other eRouška users from Bluetooth in their smartphones. If one of them later tests positive for COVID-19, the app will show the other users an anonymous alert and recommend further steps. The app can tell how close you were to other eRouška users and for what period of time. It knows that an encounter took place, but it doesn't know where.

If you have been infected, you will receive a unique code together with your test results. If you enter this code into eRouška, the app can alert potentially infected users about a risky encounter. Since they will be aware of the fact that they met with someone positive, they will be able to behave more responsibly and protect those in high risk groups.

I got an SMS, telling me I'm positive

If you received a positive PCR test result, read the detailed instructions. If the potentially infected are separated from others in time, this could prevent many more from contracting the illness.

Please, enter the code into eRouška. This information is entered anonymously. Even one code can prevent dozens of people from getting infected.

3m.title: The protection of employees
3m.content:
Rules and recommendations

Employees are currently protected by the Labor Code as usual.

All institutes contained in the Labor Code apply regardless of whether a state of emergency is declared. Even in a state of emergency, the employer cannot deviate from the legal boundaries. At the same time, the employee, as the so-called weaker unit, is very strongly protected by law.

In practice, this means that you have the same rights as you have had so far. But so you have all your responsibilities.

3n.title: Outdoor
3n.content:
Recommendations and Regulations

Obligation to cover your mouth and nose – especially with a face mask, a respirator or a scarf - needs to be followed within any urban areas of cities, towns and villages still applies.

This means between buildings, shops, in squares, and everywhere where people can be met. You do not need to wear a face covering e.g. when walking in the nature outside the city, town or village, or when alone away from other people.

Within the obligation of wearing a face mask in urban areas, there are some exemptions. The face covering does not need to be worn by children under the age of 3 or while being with people who live in the same household. This exemption also includes people who cannot wear a face covering because of a serious mental illness or intellectual impairment. It is not mandatory to wear a face covering in outside areas if a safe distance of at least 2m away from other people can be kept, however as a preventive measure we recommend wearing a face covering in any public areas. The face covering does not need to be worn while exercising e.g. while running, riding a bicycle or playground exercising.

A face mask is very effective protection that helps to prevent the spreading of viral illnesses. Even though the number of infected persons is getting lower, we recommend wearing your face covering while being outside your house. By doing this, you will protect yourself and others.

3o.title: Indoor
3o.content:
Recommendations and Regulations

Obligation to cover your mouth and nose – especially with a face mask, respirator or a scarf – needs to be followed within any indoor areas.

Within the obligation of wearing a face covering in indoor areas, there are some exemptions. The face covering does not need to be worn while being at home or other accommodation areas (e.g. especially hotel rooms). The face covering does not need to be worn by children under the age of 3 or while being with people who live in the same household. This exemption also includes people who cannot wear a face covering because of a serious mental illness or intellectual impairment.

Teachers may use a protective shield instead of a face mask when it is necessary for a pupil to see the teacher`s mouth. In such cases, the 2 meters must be maintained.

It is mandatory to wear a face mask when training indoors, only professional athletes are exempt from this rule.  

Face mask is a very effective protection that helps to prevent the spreading of viral illnesses. Therefore, we recommend wearing your face covering while being in any indoor areas. By doing this, you will protect yourself and others.

3p.title: Treatment
3p.content:
Recommendations

If you have COVID-19, you should stay in isolation, rest in bed, drink enough liquids, and contact your general practitioner. They will give you individual recommendations for symptomatic treatment.

Follow strictly all recommendations given by your doctor.

3q.title: Legal support
3q.content:
Information

If you need any legal advice and you do not know who ask, choose one of the organizations that offer free advice. You will get basic orientation in your problem and then decide what to do next. You can also find a lawyer and be represented in your case. Can't afford it? There are many options for you.

The Union of family lawyers has set up a free counselling centre. You can contact them at any time. A legal advice centre was set up to help in emergency situations (just like the Covid-19 pandemic) and you can find it on mylaw.cz. Or perhaps search for a lawyer through a search engine on the website of the Czech Bar Association.

You can also look for help from the Association of Civic Counselling Centres. It brings together organizations that provide free counselling in several legal areas, mainly to single parents, the unemployed, people living on the border of subsistence and national minorities.

Allianceprotidluhum.cz can help you orientate yourself in any debt issues and gain basic knowledge of how to deal with debts. You can also search the website for contacts in your region that can help you with your problem.

A similar project was also launched by the City of Prague in cooperation with the Faculty of Law at the Charles University. In this counselling centre, under the professional guidance of the employees of the Prague City Hall, legal consultations are provided by senior students of the Law Faculty.

Free legal advice or assistance is also offered by other non-profit organizations and associations. Your municipality or city may also provide legal advice. Ask directly at the municipal office or search the website.

In any case, beware of fraudulent companies that will only try to profit from your problem.

If you are solving a problem in the field of execution, the free counselling centres of the Bailiffs' Chamber in Prague, Brno, Pilsen and Ostrava can help you. Make sure you understand the execution process and thus avoid a number of possible problems and misunderstandings.

Visit the Department of Justice's website for answers to other common issues that may arise. 

You will also find a form for providing legal advice and the conditions of the application.

3r.title: When to seek medical attention
3r.content:
When to seek medical attention

  • If you have difficulty with breathing or a fever (higher than 38 °C) together with a dry cough, call 155 immediately and follow the operator's instructions.
  • If you have a fever that lasts for more than two days or a dry cough without a fever, contact your GP or Emergency (outside of GP's hours) and follow their instructions.
  • If you are over 60 years old and have any of the above symptoms, call your GP or Emergency (outside of GP'd hours) and follow their instructions.
     

If you do not have any of these symptoms, monitor your health regularly, and measure your temperature twice a day.

3s.title: Unemployment due to Covid-19
3s.content:
Information

If you have lost your job, it is an unpleasant situation. The following lines are here to help you find a new job as quickly as possible. Ideally, right before you become unemployed. The whole procedure of what to do was written by the Labor Office.

If you have returned from an EU / EEA / Switzerland countries where you have terminated your employment, information on what needs to be done was elaborated by Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.

We wish you good luck and just to be sure, we remind you that you will find information about possible compensations, benefits and also where to look for professional psychological help if necessary on this website.

3t.title: Diet
3t.content:
Recommendations

Food is the cornerstone of our health.

Pay attention to a healthy and balanced diet, rich in vitamins and minerals- especially vitamins C, D, E, zinc, and selenium (always follow recommended daily doses).

Eat quality food that isn't industrially processed and do not forget about fruit and vegetables.

3u.title: I recovered from COVID-19
3u.content:
Recommendations

No one knows exactly how long you are immune for after recovering from COVID-19. Experts have agreed that it is at least 90 days. After recovering, you still have the antibodies in your blood from when you were sick. New ones are not created and the old ones gradually disappear from your body.

If you had COVID-19 recently and want to help the patients who have a challenging course of the illness, you can donate plasma. It contains protein antibodies and its donation can help save lives.

3v.title: Penalties for not wearing a face masks
3v.content:
Regulations

The Emergency Measures of the Ministry of Health states a general obligation to wear a face mask. This is monitored by municipal and also by state police forces. You can get a penalty up to 10,000 CZK if you fail to comply, however, the police can give you only a warning in case of a less major offence. The penalty is payable immediately, or later on during an administrative procedure.

If you fail to comply with a quarantine or a self-isolation, it can be treated as a criminal offence of spreading a contagious illness.

Source

Police jurisdiction to monitor the public of wearing face masks is stated by a Special Law. Penalties are stated by the Act No. 258/2000 Coll., on the protection of public health (§ 92n, paragraph 1b of this Act), and by the Act No. 250/2016 Coll.,on the liability for offences and proceedings concerning them (§ 91 of this Act).

3w.title: When we will have the vaccine?
3w.content:
Information

Since the beginning of the pandemic researchers around the world have been trying to create a safe vaccine against the new coronavirus.

Thanks to the conditions contracted by the European Union, the Czech Republic plans to buy 3 million doses of the vaccine from AstraZeneca, which cooperates with experts from the University of Oxford.

The first delivery is scheduled for January or February 2021.

European Commission is currently negotiating a deal with Pfizer and BioNTech for the 3rd generation vaccine with efficacy close to 95 %.

The Czech Republic joined a non-binding agreement of the supply of vaccines. This agreement with Pfizer and BioNTech was guided by the European Commission. The Czech Republic is supposed to obtain 2 million doses of the vaccine.

3x.title: Retraining
3x.content:
Rules and recommendations

Retraining is an active employment policy tool that enables individuals to obtain a qualification for a new job or to maintain an existing job. The determination of the content is based on the current qualifications, health status, abilities and experiences of a person to be retrained. Retraining is provided by the Labour Office competent according to the place of residence of the job seeker.

All necessary information can be found on the website of the Labor Office.

3y.title: Work experience
3y.content:
Rules and recommendations

Work experience is permitted to students in groups of less than 20 people.

Please, wear a mask and follow all hygienic recommendations.

3z.title: What does the R value mean?
3z.content:
The R number describes how quickly the disease spreads, or how many people get infected on average from one COVID-19 positive person.

If R is greater than 1, then the number of newly infected people will continue to increase.

If R is less than 1, the number of newly infected people will decrease.

How to reduce the R number?

The baseline R number for SARS-CoV-2 in a population without any restrictions is around 3. Face masks, social distancing and other quarantine-type measures reduce the R number, which is now around 1.

Even though R-value is at 1, there are still a lot of infectious people. If anti-epidemic measures are not followed the virus can get out of control very soon.

The virus spreads at an exponential rate. Exactly what is described in the story of the origin of chess.

What can I do to reduce the R number?

Any value higher than 1 means that we are not yet at the peak of the epidemic because the number of active infections is still rising. Every decimal point counts.

Respecting the current measures against the spread of the disease and following hygiene rules is the most effective weapon any of us have in the fight against any contagious disease.

4a.title: Company canteens
4a.content:
Rules and recommendations

Company catering may continue to be in operation. However, government action has several rules:

  • customers are seated so that there is a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them (this does not apply if they are sitting at one table),
  • a maximum of 4 people can sit at one table (except for household members), if it is a long table, there must be a distance of at least 2 meters between the groups (the exception is again household members),
  • the operator will not allow more customers in the interior than there are customer seats,
  • the operator is obliged to record in writing the total current number of seats for customers,
  • in the case of persons who consume food and meals outside the catering establishment, but in its proximity (e.g. the dispensing window), the distance between persons must be at least 2 meters, unless they are household members,
  • for hygienic reasons, it is recommended to use non-cash payments as a matter of priority,
  • the operator must also ensure the possibility of hand disinfection when entering indoor and outdoor areas.

Customers must be encouraged by information materials to maintain a distance in the queues of at least 2 meters.

4b.title: Schools defined in § 16 of Act 561/2004 Coll.
4b.content:
Rules and recommendations

The personal presence of students in special schools is allowed.

Pupils and teachers do not have to have their mouths and noses covered during teaching.

Groups of individual classes must not merge and intersect. It is necessary to maintain the homogeneity of the class groups.

4c.title: Purpose of the measures
4c.content:
What is the purpose of the measures?

The purpose of the governmental measures is to reduce the reproductive number of COVID-19 to such an extent, that the health care system of the Czech Republic can manage the epidemic and not have to limit care for patients in order to increase the number of available hospital beds for those with COVID-19.

Flattening the curve will give the healthcare system time to care for patients with COVID-19.

The next step is to bring the COVID-19 epidemic under control, that is, to prevent the so-called community-based spread of the disease. Each of us can individually contribute to reducing the R number by respecting all hygiene recommendations and limiting contact with other people.

Please follow all of the hygienic measures, especially: wearing your mask, disinfecting your hands, and social distancing.

4d.title: State of Emergency
4d.content:
State of Emergency

The state of emergency is one of the extraordinary measures of the Constitutional Act on the Security of the Czech Republic. It is announced by the government.

One of the cases in which the government can declare a state of emergency is in the situation when there is a dangerous or significant threat to our lives or health. And this is the current case.

The government can declare a state of emergency for a maximum of 30 days. However, this situation may be extended with the prior consent of the Chamber of Deputies.

The state of emergency ends with the expiration of the period for which it was declared or with a decision to cancel it. The Government or the Chamber of Deputies can cancel the state of emergency.

Crisis measures

These are measures intended to eliminate or ease the consequences of these difficult times.

The implementation of a crisis measure can restrict certain rights and freedoms and impose specific obligations. Crisis measures may be issued by the government in the event of a declared state of emergency based on the law on Crisis Management and on the Amendment of Certain laws (Crisis Act).

The effectiveness of crisis measures was prolonged for the duration of the state of emergency.

4e.title: School counseling facilities
4e.content:
Rules and recommendations

School counseling services can continue to work without restrictions. It is, however, necessary to follow all hygienic regulations. It is essential to cover a nose and mouth when in contact with people in person.

We do not recommend to take part in group activities. It could increase the risk of infection as this would put the participants and their loved ones at risk.

Some schools offer the services of school psychologists alongside the school counselors. The current situation can take a toll on one's mental health, so do not hesitate to ask for help. If you do not know whether your school offers the services of a psychologist, reach out to your teachers. You can also look for advice in the Stress and handling impacts of the pandemic section.

4f.title: Homework, exams and evaluation
4f.content:
Pravidla a doporučení

Pro žáky a studenty, kteří nemají povoleno účastnit se prezenční výuky, je zajišťována výuka distanční formou.

Povolují se individuální konzultace ve škole, kde může kromě žáka a vyučujícího být přítomen také zákonný zástupce dítěte.

Pro žáky plnící povinnou školní docházku je účast na distanční výuce povinná. Hodnocení tak vychází i z práce, kterou žák odvedl v rámci online výuky. Je třeba sledovat pokyny jednotlivých učitelů, aby žák plnil veškeré školní povinnosti včetně úkolů.

Studentům středních škol doporučujeme sledovat pravidla pro distanční výuku, kterou stanoví jak vedení školy, tak jednotliví učitelé. Hodnocení bude vycházet z aktivity spojené i s distanční výukou. Doporučujeme proto sledovat termíny dodání domácích úkolů.

Pedagogové mohou studenty a žáky zkoušet ať už písemnou, ústní či jinou formou i v průběhu distanční výuky.

Zatím není známá metodika závěrečného hodnocení na konci pololetí. Informace o podobě hodnocení na pololetním vysvědčení budeme aktualizovat na tomto webu. Více informací o tom, jak úspěšně zvládat distanční výuku, najdete v sekci Distanční výuka.

Pro studenty vysokých škol doporučujeme sledovat pokyny studijních oddělení a jednotlivých vyučujících. Zkoušky se mohou konat do počtu 10 osob. S přiblížením zkouškového období je tak třeba sledovat pravidla ukončení jednotlivých kurzů a s tím spojenou podobu zkoušení, ale také vypsané termíny zkoušení.

4g.title: Shift work
4g.content:
Rules and recommendations

General hygiene rules at the workplace apply to shift work. 

The specifics of shift operation is the alternation of shifts. In these situations, it is highly recommended that you do not come into contact with other shift workers. It is therefore recommended to limit the number of people in changing rooms and showers, especially for manual work . The ideal scenario would be to divide employees into several teams or groups that will not meet in the workplace at the same time.

Recommendations of the Chamber of Commerce.

4h.title: Volunteer firefighters
4h.content:
V současné době se dobrovolní hasiči v běžném provozu musí řídit všemi mimořádnými opatřeními. 

Jsou povoleny zkoušky týkající se členů požární ochrany a příslušníků Hasičského záchranného sboru České republiky. 

Při výjezdu musí být hasiči vybaveni ochrannými prostředky, které jsou přizpůsobeny ke druhu zásahu. Při všech činnostech je také nutné dle situace dbát na maximální dodržování hygienických opatření.

4i.title: Breeders
4i.content:
It is possible to organize exhibitions and competitions. However, there is a limit to the number of people, the maximum of 50 people for outdoor events, 10 people for indoor events.  

All hygiene measures must continue to be follow (masks, hands and spacing).

4j.title: Distance learning
4j.content:
Rules and recommendations

For students who are not currently allowed a personal presence in class, they are continuing remotely.

Participation in distance learning is compulsory for pupils. In the case of compulsory school attendance, the child must be excused within 3 working days. When distance learning is in place follow the instructions you receive from teachers and the school. Especially at higher levels of education please follow the website and instructions given by the study department.

Distance learning depends on the possibility of a remote connection. If you do not have the necessary equipment to complete this type of teaching, contact the school and ask for help. They should be ready to assist you in these types of situations, and if their supplies are limited, they will advise you to get the help you need in a different place. For example, non-profit organizations can also help you with your difficulties.

At present we are dealing with a number of new challenges, including distance learning. For both teachers and pupils and their parents, distance education is usually something new to them and they need time to adjust. Therefore, please be helpful and understand the needs of each other. We do not replace full-time teaching, but you can also learn a lot online.

To successfully manage distance learning, we recommend setting up a schedule: Get up at a regular hour. Create a workspace. Do not go to bed to connect to your lessons. Schedule your tasks and responsibilities. Make notes, it will help you keep attention. Communicate with teachers and classmates. Don't be afraid to ask at any time.

4k.title: Membership meetings
4k.content:
Rules and recommendations

It is impossible to hold membership meetings at the moment. However, the law has been passed in response to the effects of the epidemic on legal persons.

In practice, there may be situations where a member meeting of the association needs to decide on a certain issue, but it is not possible to meet. For these cases, the law defines the rules for how to take a decision for the duration of the exceptional measures, even if this is not enshrined in the articles of association. Specifically, it is the possibility of using technical means (eg. teleconferencing) or decision-making by correspondence voting (i.e. by mail or email).

The possibility applies in general to legal entities, i.e. it is not only about associations, but also, for example, SVJ.

The law also regulates the situation where a member of the body of a legal entity ends his term of office and it is not possible to agree on the extension or renewal of his office. In case of disagreement of a member with the extension of the term of office, it will be possible to solve this problem by so-called co-option. That is, the current members of this body will be able to choose a new member of the body, even if the charter does not allow it.

However, it is necessary to emphasize that the measures for legal entities are valid only until 31 December 2020, otherwise it is necessary to enshrine them into the founding legal proceedings!

4l.title: Lecturing
4l.content:
Congresses, meetings and other similar events are allowed in a maximum of 10 people.

All hygiene measures must continue to be follow (masks, hands and spacing).

4m.title: Halls of residence
4m.content:
Rules and recommendations

Students who attend classes in-person can stay at dorms and school housing. 

If are you staying at school housing, please follow thoroughly hygienic recommendations.

4n.title: Fishing
4n.content:
Výkon rybářského práva je povolen. 

Není ani omezen výkon funkce rybářské stráže. Povoleny jsou i činnosti v rybářském revíru, které nelze odložit (např. zarybňování). Povoleny jsou také rybářské zkoušky. 

Při provádění výlovů rybníků v zastavěném území obce nemusí osoby provádějící výlov používat v rybníku ochranných prostředků dýchacích cest, jsou však povinny udržovat minimální rozestupy.

4o.title: Students' work duty
4o.content:
Government measure on students' work duty is changed from midnight 10.12. 2020. Students' work duty now does not apply to 4th and 5th-year medical students of general medicine. (Students must attend proximity studies on the public university)

 

Nové se pracovní povinnost nebude vztahovat na studenty čtvrtého a pátého ročníku prezenční formy studijního programu všeobecné lékařství na lékařských fakultách veřejných vysokých škol.

Rules and recommendations

The whole system is under strain at the moment, so work duty has been introduced for students of specific fields.

In medical fields, this applies to 4th and 5th-year medical students of general medicine, 5th-year dental students, 5th-year pharmacy, students preparing for non-doctoral medical studies, Masters students of psychology, or students in their last year of medical secondary school. See the complete list (in Czech). 

Work duty also applies to students of pedagogical fields.

The right to issue the order lays in hands of specific regional authority, based on the permanent residence of the student. Once being selected, the order will be sent to you. Work duty could be ordered at any time during the state of emergency.

Travels related to work duty are exempt from the ban on free movement.

Thank you for your help during these tough times.

4p.title: Psychological help for children and students
4p.content:
Recommendation

A pandemic is a difficult time for everyone, so it is normal not to feel well.

Recommendations in Czech for teenagers were prepared by the organization Nevypusť Duši.

You can learn more about the basic recommendations for psycho-hygiene during a pandemic in Stress and handling impacts of a pandemic section.

If necessary, contact one of the lines taught for children and young people:

  • Line of Safety (Association of Lines of Safety): 116 111 (nonstop), FREE help for children, young people, and students under 26 years of age
  • Children's Crisis Center Helpline: 777 715 215, 241 484 149 (nonstop) for children and adults
  • Crisis line SOS center Diakonie: 800 567 567 (daily 9-20), FREE

4q.title: Psychological help for parents
4q.content:
Recommendations for handling the state of emergency

Being in some form of isolation or quarantine can be very challenging. If possible, still maintain your social contacts through the online world during this time. Try to keep your own habits and as constant as possible. It is important to eat in a balanced way, to have enough sleep and rest, and also to strive for physical and mental activity. It's a good idea to use stress management methods that have worked for you before and have proven to be effective. There are many ways to reduce stress, such as relaxation or meditation.

You can learn about the basic recommendations for maintaining mental health in the Mental hygiene section.

If you feel that you need to talk to someone, either about a specific problem or just to talk, contact one of the crisis lines. You can find a list of them in the Psychological help section.

Recommendations for managing cohabitation in an emergency 

Spending quarantine in a couple or family can be an advantage and a disadvantage. You and your partner and family can support each other, but there is also a risk that in time you will "start getting on each other's nerves."

What to do to avoid conflicts?  

  • It is essential to arm yourself with a dose of patience and tolerance - with a pandemic, the dynamics of your coexistence are likely to change significantly, and it will take everyone a long time to come to terms with the situation.
  • Try to divide the time into the time spent on joint activities and the time that each of you devotes to yourself.
  • If there are also children in the household, try to divide taking care of them.
  • These times are also demanding in terms of worries and fears - about the health of loved ones, about the future. Try to talk to your partner about your concerns.
  • Do not bottle your feelings inside, try, and talk about them with your partner and children. If you resolve the dispute right away, the situation is far less likely to escalate.
  • Remember that the situation also affects children. They don't see friends, they have nowhere to exhaust their energy. If you suddenly find the space of the apartment smaller than usual, try to go for a walk in the fresh air. A short walk will certainly benefit you.
  • Have some fun - watch a movie, cook with your family or play a board game.

4r.title: Hunting
4r.content:
Výkon práva myslivosti je povolen.

Povolen je společný i individuální lov za účelem plnění plánu lovu a předcházení škodám zvěří (např. společný lov drobné zvěře).

V případě společného lovu se musí dodržovat rozestupy a mít nasazené roušky. V současné době je možné pořádat zkoušky z myslivosti a zkoušky mysliveckých hospodářů. 

Zároveň není omezen výkon funkce myslivecké stráže.

4s.title: Domestic violence prevention
4s.content:
Recommendations

If you feel threatened by your partner or another household member due to mental, physical or sexual violence or coercion, immediately contact the helpline for domestic violence.

  • Crime and Domestic Violence Helpline White Circle of Safety: 116 006 (non-stop), FREE help for victims.
  • Helpline for victims of domestic and sexual violence proFem +420 608 222 277, social worker - Monday to Friday from 9am to 15pm, the legal helpline for victims of domestic and sexual violence - Tuesday from 9am to 12pm and Wednesday from 5:30pm to 8:30pm.
  • ROSA helpline for victims of domestic violence: +420 241 432 466 (mon, tue 9:00-18:00, wed, thu from 9am to 4pm, fri from 9am to 2pm, SOS line: +420 602 246 102 (mon-fri from 9am to 6pm, +420 739 709  764 (mon, tue from 9am to 6pm wed, thu from 9am to 4pm, fri from 9am to 2pm).

In case of a direct threat, please contact Police of the Czech Republic on line 158.

4t.title: After-school activities
4t.content:
Rules and recommendations

Students who attend school in-person can take a part in after-school activities. The number of people in one class is restricted to 10.

During after-school activities, the homogenous groups should stay the same. Students from different classes should not meet each other.

Individual classes and consultations are permitted.

4u.title: Students: the return home
4u.content:
Pravidla a doporučení

Nyní je omezen provoz ubytování na kolejích a internátech. 

Pokud se vracíte domů ke své rodině, můžete využít možnost bezodkladného testování na Covid-19 prostřednictvím mobilních odběrových týmů. Na výsledek testu, prosím, počkejte v izolaci, zabráníte tak možnému kontaktu s nakaženým a následnému přenesení na vaše blízké.

Pokud bude výsledek testu pozitivní, buďte v karanténě nejlépe ve svém pokoji na koleji. Stejný postup doporučujeme, pokud se už v karanténě nacházíte. Tedy dokončete ji na koleji a až pak se vypravte domů za rodinou.

V případě psychických obtíží spojených s izolací, strachu z nemoci nebo obav o blízké se podívejte níže do okruhu Stres a zvládání dopadů pandemie.

Po návratu domů je student vnímám jako člen domácnosti, do které se vrátil. Vztahují se tak na něj vládní opatření pro členy jedné domácnosti.

Pokud chcete jet navštívit rodinu na víkend, zvažte prosím veškerá rizika přenosu nákazy na vaše blízké. Snížit riziko nákazy se dá například důkladným dodržováním hygienických opatření.

4v.title: Cohabitation in the state of emergency
4v.content:
Recommendations for surviving in the state of emergency

Being in some form of isolation or quarantine can be very challenging. If possible, keep your social contacts through the online platforms during this time. Try to keep your habits and routines as constant as possible. It is important to eat balanced meals, have enough sleep and rest, and also aim for physical and mental activity. It is a good idea to keep using stress management methods that have worked for you before and have proven to be effective. There are many ways to reduce stress, such as relaxation or meditation.

You can learn about the fundamental recommendations for maintaining mental health in section Stress and handling the impacts of the pandemic > Mental hygiene.

If you feel that you need to talk to someone, either about a specific problem or just to be in contact with someone, reach to one of the crisis lines. You can find a list of them in section Stress and handling the impacts of the pandemic > Psychological help.

Recommendations for coping with cohabitation in the state of emergency

Spending quarantine in a couple or with family can be an advantage as well as a disadvantage. You and your partner and family can support each other, but there is also a risk that in some time, you will "start getting on each other's nerves."

What to do to avoid conflicts?

  1. It is essential to arm yourself with a dose of patience and tolerance - with a pandemic, the dynamics of your coexistence are likely to change, and it takes everyone some time to come to terms with the situation.
  2. Try to divide the time into the time spent on joint activities and the time for yourself.
  3. If there are children in your household, try to divide the care equivalently.
  4. These times can also be exhausting in terms of your worries. You can have concerns about the health of loved ones or the future. Try to open to your partner and talk about your anxieties.
  5. Do not stifle your feelings inside of you and try to talk about them with your partner and children. If you resolve disputes straight away, there is far less risk that the situation would escalate.
  6. Remember that the situation also affects children. They cannot see their friends, and they do not have that many options where to drain their energy. If you suddenly find the space in your apartment smaller than usual, try to go for a walk on the fresh air. A short walk will surely help you.
  7. Have some fun - watch a movie, cook with your family or play a board game.

4w.title: Libraries
4w.content:
Rules and recommendations

Libraries operate in a restricted mode.

They are publicly accessible under maintaining the 15 sq m rule as well as other hygienic precautions (wearing a mask, keeping a 2-meter distance from others, etc.).

If you need to know, which rules for borrowing books your library has set, please refer to its website.

Please try to replace books and their physical receiving - be it for studying, your job or just for fun - with online source databases. For their overview please refer to the desired library website as well.

University students are usually offered access to the databases for free - for exact access options please search the website of your institution.

4x.title: Chess
4x.content: Chess tournaments can take place with a maximum of 10 people. All participants must wear masks and follow hygiene measures.

4y.title: Children´s associations
4y.content:
Rules and recommendations

There is a limit on the number of people for all activities. A maximum of 50 people is valid for outdoor activities, for indoor activities it is a maximum of 10 people. 

All hygienic measures must continue to be follow (masks, hands and spacing).

4z.title: I´m a teacher
4z.content:
Rules and recommendations

It goes without saying that you can attend school, if you are a teacher of students that take part in the full-time teaching. In this case, observe the hygiene recommendations and measures:

  • Face masks are compulsory for both students and teachers.
  • We recommend frequent ventilation in classrooms and common areas (5 minutes between hours and in the middle of each hour, or every 30 minutes).
  • It is recommended to stay on the fresh air as much as possible.
  • We recommend organizing the movement of students within the school area (including arrival and departure) so as to limit the contact.
  • Singing and sports activities are prohibited.

Home office is recommended for all pedagogical professions. Therefore, you should provide an online teaching from your home. However, if you do not have the necessary equipment at home, it is possible to go to school and teach from an empty classroom or your cabinet. However, please observe the increased hygiene measures, especially the Wear Z (face masks, social distance and disinfect your hands).

Distance learning is not only a complex challenge for students, but also for teachers. Many of us are just learning how to use the online tools. It is a good opportunity for you to learn something new and expand your skills as well as helping your students. The teacher's interpretation is irreplaceable during the study and students will certainly appreciate your effort to mediate it, at least remotely.

The current situation is very demanding. Especially with the increased stress that a change in the type of teaching entails. Don't be afraid to ask for help. See Stress and Pandemic Impact Management for more information.

If you need technical help, perhaps you can ask your children for help/or even students. They will be happy to help you and pass on their experience.

Inspiration

On the website of the Ministry of Education, Youth and Sports, you will find a lot of useful tips for online teaching.

5a.title: Notaries, lawyers, executors
5a.content:
Rules and Recommendations

The general ban on service providers does not apply to lawyers, notaries, or executors. You can continue to use their services, upon agreement with their office.

Lawyers, notaries, and executors can issue their specific measures, so contact them directly for more detailed information.

5b.title: Household (shopping, repairs etc.)
5b.content:
Rules and recommendations

Shopping

For details on how stores work, please see Shops and Services > Retail.

Repairs

For details on the operation of services and repairs, please see Shops and Services > Repairs and Services.

Craftsmen

Craftspeople can still visit and work in households, as government measures apply only to performing services in the store. However, please try to use their services only when necessary. You should postpone minor repairs.

During their visit, it is necessary to follow hygienic measures. Everyone present should wear a face mask and keep a distance from each other.

Use your own pen for signing, and if possible, prefer non-cash payment (transfers, card payments, etc.). Cash circulates in the hands of a vast number of people every day. By choosing contactless payments, you can help reduce the risk of infection.

If someone from your household is in quarantine or isolation, it is necessary to cancel the visit of a craftsman. In the event of an emergency where the repair cannot be postponed, you must inform the craftsman about the presence of infected person prior to the visit. Infected person should not meet the craftsman under any circumstances.

5c.title: STK
5c.content:
Rules and recommendations

STK (vehicle inspection) remains in operation. You can still book technical inspections. Please remember that driving without a valid SKT is a minor offense even in times of a state of emergency.

5d.title: Pets
5d.content:
Rules and recommendations

Animals and Covid-19

There are rare cases where pets had been infected by COVID -19. So far, we have limited information about the effects of this disease on animals, so treat your pet like any other member of the household. If there is an infected person in your house, reduce the contact between the infected and the animal to a minimum.

Remember, that virus can be transmitted on the animal's fur, so wash and disinfect your hands thoroughly before and after contact with the animal. Do not let strangers stroke your pet.

Visits to the vet

Before the visit, always call the veterinarian and consult with him whether your appointment is necessary. Stay in the waiting room only for the inevitable time and keep a two-meters distance from other people in the room. Wearing a face mask is a must. Try to avoid touching objects that had been touched by people before you, such as handles or railings.

Always inform your veterinarian if you think you have met an infected or quarantined person!

Walking the dog in isolation or quarantine

If you have to quarantine or go to isolation, you should ask someone to walk your dog for you. During the transmission, please pay extra attention to hygiene measure - wear a face mask or respirator, ideally put on gloves and wash and disinfect your hands thoroughly before and after.

The quarantined or isolated person can only walk the dog when there is no one else to do it for him/her. If this situation occurs, please take your dog out only for the necessary time. When staying outside, avoid places with a higher concentration of people, wear a face mask and keep a two-meters distance.

5e.title: Execution of the sentence imprisonment
5e.content:
Rules and recommendations

In a state of emergency visits to prisons, remand prisons, and security detention facilities are prohibited. The ban is compensated by extending a possibility to have a call for 30 minutes per day. Also, prisoners are allowed to have a videocalls with their loved ones.

Lawyers can go to prisons on behalf of clients. However, they must face masks in all of the areas of the facility, including dealings with the client. Lawyers can also communicate with clients online using the "Skype Defense" program.

5f.title: Courts
5f.content:
Rules and Recommendations

The courts continue functioning even in times of emergency, but it's necessary to follow the general rules, especially to observe hygienic measures (wear a face mask, social distance, and disinfect your hands), give priority to written communication, and follow the rules of conduct in the courthouse.

Court proceedings may take place, but judges should consider the epidemiological situation, the urgency of the proceedings (time limits), and the need for a personal presence at the hearing when the ruling is made.

The public may be present at the trial but must wear a face mask at all times. This will protect themselves and others in the courtroom.

When visiting the courts, it is necessary to follow increased hygienic measures - the court building can only be entered after prior hand disinfection. At the entrance to the courthouse, you may be asked to provide a statement that you do not have an infectious disease, fever, or symptoms of respiratory disease (especially coughing, sneezing, breathing difficulties).

It is necessary to wear a face mask in the court building at all times. Exceptions to the obligation to wear a face mask at the time of court proceedings apply to judges and jurors, public prosecutors, the accused, their lawyer, hearing participants and their representatives, witnesses, court experts, translators, and other persons for whom the court allows not to wear a face mask.

Inspection of the files is possible only in necessary cases (e.g. if the statutory deadline was missed or in the case of ordered proceedings) and after prior agreement.

Prefer written or electronic communication with the courts. An online data-box can also be used to communicate with the courts.

Specific courts can take their own measures, which can be found on the website of a specific court.

5g.title: The return home
5g.content:
Pravidla a doporučení

Nyní je omezen provoz ubytování na kolejích a internátech. 

Pokud se vracíte domů ke své rodině, můžete využít možnost bezodkladného testování na Covid-19 prostřednictvím mobilních odběrových týmů. Na výsledek testu, prosím, počkejte v izolaci, zabráníte tak možnému kontaktu s nakaženým a následnému přenesení na vaše blízké.

Pokud bude výsledek testu pozitivní, buďte v karanténě nejlépe ve svém pokoji na koleji. Stejný postup doporučujeme, pokud se už v karanténě nacházíte. Tedy dokončete ji na koleji a až pak se vypravte domů za rodinou.

V případě psychických obtíží spojených s izolací, strachu z nemoci nebo obav o blízké se podívejte níže do okruhu Stres a zvládání dopadů pandemie.

Po návratu domů je student vnímám jako člen domácnosti, do které se vrátil. Vztahují se tak na něj vládní opatření pro členy jedné domácnosti.

Pokud chcete jet navštívit rodinu na víkend, zvažte prosím veškerá rizika přenosu nákazy na vaše blízké. Snížit riziko nákazy se dá například důkladným dodržováním hygienických opatření.

5h.title: Retail
5h.content:
Rules and recommendations

The operation of all shops and stores is allowed, but hygienic rules have to be strictly followed. Bear in mind that COVID-19 did not disappear with the lift of bans on free movement and on shops and services. Be considerate to other people inside shops, follow strictly hygienic rules, try to avoid close distance contact – keep at least 2 meters distance from other people, and wear face masks all the time.

Opening hours

Opening hours are no longer limited by special crisis measures.

Hygiene rules

When going shopping follow strict hygienic rules. Wearing a face mask and keeping a 2-meter distance from other customers is mandatory, especially when waiting in a queue. Every time you enter a shop disinfection gel or spray need to be available at the entrance – use it. On arrival back home wash your hands. 

Shopping with disposable gloves increases the protection against the virus. Do not touch surfaces unnecessarily. Bakery products, fruits, and vegetables touch ONLY with the gloves on or use a disposable plastic bag.

A group of a maximum of 10 persons is allowed to enter a shop. The exemption is people living in the same household. The maximum number of persons allowed in a shop is limited by the sales to 1 person per 15m^2. 

In stores with an area of less than 15m^2, this restriction will not affect adolescents younger than 15 years of age, handicapped people owning a ZTP card. In stores, larger than 15m^2 exemption to the total number of people inside will be kids younger than 6 years of age accompanying another customer. Handicapped people owning a ZTP card will have the privilege to enter the shop first in line, so they will not have to wait in queues. Owners and operators of shops and stores must not require a person with a stroller to enter only with a shopping cart. A child in a stroller is not counted within the maximum limit of 15m^2 per shopping area.

It is also mandatory to adopt regime and organizational measures and queue management (in front of and in the shop).

Even though the epidemic situation is slightly better, try to buy products on e-shops. When coming personally to a shop it is recommended to pay by a credit or debit card.

If you are part of a higher risk group or are in quarantine (isolation), ask a neighbor, relative, or friend to do your shopping. If this isn't possible, you can reach out to volunteers. Help and deliveries to high-risk groups and the infected), who will be happy to help. You can also order online and get your shopping delivered to your doorstep.

5i.title: Halls of residence
5i.content:
Rules and recommendations

Students who attend classes in-person can stay at dorms and school housing. 

If are you staying at school housing, please follow thoroughly hygienic recommendations.

5j.title: Meeting friends
5j.content:
Rules and recommendations

The free movement of people is not restricted for the moment. It is important to consider the risk of each contact with other people. It is vital to abide by all the hygiene rules and recommendations.

The current situation is very stressful for maintaining mental well-being. If you suffer from mental health problems, information from the Stress and Pandemic Impact Management might be useful for you.

Although, online platforms do not replace personal contact a meeting is not recommended. When a meeting is necessary, you can choose outdoor areas for example, and don't forget to wear a face mask.

You can find more about the meeting and relevant current measures in section Meetings, parties, family celebrations.

5k.title: Distance learning
5k.content:
Rules and recommendations

For students who are not currently allowed a personal presence in class, they are continuing remotely.

Participation in distance learning is compulsory for pupils. In the case of compulsory school attendance, the child must be excused within 3 working days. When distance learning is in place follow the instructions you receive from teachers and the school. Especially at higher levels of education please follow the website and instructions given by the study department.

Distance learning depends on the possibility of a remote connection. If you do not have the necessary equipment to complete this type of teaching, contact the school and ask for help. They should be ready to assist you in these types of situations, and if their supplies are limited, they will advise you to get the help you need in a different place. For example, non-profit organizations can also help you with your difficulties.

At present we are dealing with a number of new challenges, including distance learning. For both teachers and pupils and their parents, distance education is usually something new to them and they need time to adjust. Therefore, please be helpful and understand the needs of each other. We do not replace full-time teaching, but you can also learn a lot online.

To successfully manage distance learning, we recommend setting up a schedule: Get up at a regular hour. Create a workspace. Do not go to bed to connect to your lessons. Schedule your tasks and responsibilities. Make notes, it will help you keep attention. Communicate with teachers and classmates. Don't be afraid to ask at any time.

5l.title: How does tracing work?
5l.content:
The goal of tracing

The goal of tracing is to quickly identify potentially infected people, quarantine them, and protect the public.

Self-tracing

If you are infected with COVID-19, contact the people who you could have potentially infected.

I want to self-trace, but from when?

I am asymptomatic: All epidemiologically significant contacts from 5 days up to 1 week before the date of receiving the COVID -19 positive PCR test.

I have symptoms of COVID -19: All epidemiologically significant contacts for 2 days before the onset of the first symptoms until the date of receiving a positive PCR test.

Self-tracing form

After receiving the results of the positive test, you will also receive a link to the self-tracing form to your telephone number, where you can fill in the tracing data. Self-tracing forms are processed as a priority by the Regional Health Authority (KHS or Krajská hygienická stanice in Czech).

Call from the Health Authority or tracing center

An employee of the health Authority or tracing center will call you and ask for your tracing information (prepare it in advance).

Prepare the following data for tracing:

  • name and surname of the contact
  • their telephone number
  • the day of the last contact with this person (if you are in the same household, the day of the last contact is the day of the positive PCR test).

Due to the amount of work, the hygiene station may contact you a few days after taking a positive test, so it is best to fill out a self-tracing form or call and inform your contacts yourself.

eRouška

If you use the eRouška application, you will receive an SMS code to your telephone number after the results of the positive test have been received. By entering the SMS code into the application, the people who the application has evaluated as your risky contacts will be automatically informed. The data is anonymous, so you don't have to be afraid to insert it in eRouška. Even one code can prevent dozens from getting infected.

5m.title: Divorced families
5m.content:
Rules and recommendations

The child has the right to see both parents even during a state of emergency. There is currently no restriction on the free movement of people.

From a legal point of view, therefore, there is no reason not to comply with the court's decision concerning children.

On the other hand, it is necessary to consider all the risks and try to create rules that reduce the possibility of disease transmission. Especially if the risk of infection is higher for one of the parents (such as health professionals or other people who are in contact with the sick or more people). However, such adjustments to the regime should be based on the agreement of both parents.

We recommend maintaining contact with the child through telephone calls, video calls, and other tools that allow at least alternative contact if quarantine or other measures do not allow personal contact.

A change in alternating care is also strongly recommended in case when one of the parents finds themself in isolation or quarantine. In this case, the transfer of the child should not take place. If the child is in the care of a parent who has to start quarantine for some reason, the child should remain in quarantine with that parent. If, on the other hand, the child is currently in the care of one parent and should transfer to a parent who has to start or is in quarantine as part of alternating care, we recommend that this transfer not take place.

5n.title: Visits in hospitals
5n.content:
Nařízení

Návštěvy pacientů u všech poskytovatelů zdravotních služeb ve zdravotnických zařízeních, ve kterých se poskytuje lůžková péče jsou zakázány.
Výjimkou jsou pouze návštěvy nezletilých pacientů, pacientů s omezenou svéprávností a pacientů v hospicech a dalších pacientů v terminálním stadiu nevyléčitelného onemocnění.

Účast třetí osoby u porodu

Účast třetí osoby při porodu je povolena za předpokladu, že je splněny podmínky:

  • Třetí osobou je druhý rodič dítěte nebo osoba žijící s rodičkou ve společné domácnosti.
  • Porod bude probíhat v samostatném porodním pokoji nebo boxu s vlastním sociálním zařízením.
  • Bude zamezen kontakt třetí osoby s ostatními rodičkami.
  • Třetí osoba se podrobí měření teploty před vstupem do porodního pokoje nebo boxu.
  • Třetí osoba má tělesnou teplotou nedosahující 37,0 °C a zároveň nemá příznaky onemocnění covid-19.
  • Třetí osoba používá chirurgickou roušku jako minimální ochranu dýchacích cest (Nechirurgické a látkové roušky či šály nestačí!!)

Sledujte prosím nařízení a pravidla konkrétních nemocnic.

5o.title: Work-agreements and self-employed
5o.content:
Recommendation

If you have lost income or lost part of it as a result of the coronavirus crisis, use one of the state compensation options. Apply for compensation if you are self-employed (OSVč) or employed on DPP / DPČ. This is a bonus of 500 crowns for each day when the establishment was closed, or your business was prevented or restricted. You can find more detailed conditions for obtaining compensation in the Compensation bonus section.

If you do business in the affected sector of culture, you, unfortunately, cannot apply for compensation.

If you are renting an establishment that you have had to close as a result of government regulations, see also COVID - Rent II section.

The Ministry also allows for the deferral of tax obligations. You can find more about deferrals in the Large Tax Liberation Package section.

5p.title: Non-emergency care
5p.content:
Recommendations

Contact your hospital or polyclinic and get the information on the provision of non-emergency care.

Do not, however, postpone preventative checkups.

5q.title: Hygiene recommendations for children and students
5q.content:
Recommendation

 

To best prevent the spread of coronavirus, it is important to follow the rule: Face mask, hand sanitation, social distance.

Wearing a face mask (over your mouth and nose) is one of the most effective prevention against coronavirus infection. A face mask is effective only if it covers the entire area of ​​the nose and mouth. The face mask must be worn indoors, but also in villages and towns. Learn how to handle a face mask safely in the Face masks section.

Another important prevention is frequent and thorough hand washing and the use of disinfection. In this way, you can prevent the infection from getting into your body (mostly mouth, nose, and eyes) from your hands, from where the virus can then spread to your body.

It is also important to keep a gap in a place with a higher concentration of people. The recommended distance you should keep is 2 meters.

All these methods of prevention protect not only you but also your loved ones, parents, grandparents, and other people who could fall into the risk category for whom the coronavirus is particularly dangerous.

5r.title: Playgrounds
5r.content:
Rules and recommendations

Public playgrounds are open. However, it is important to follow all government regulations in their area to prevent the transmission of the disease to your home and loved ones.

Currently, it is necessary to wear a face mask when in a village or town. This also applies to playgrounds.

Also, keep a distance of 2 meters from other people and do not associate. Try to make sure that children behave within the framework of these recommendations.

Do not enter the field of play if it is already so busy that it would not be possible to keep distances from other people. In this case, consider the security of the area and the risk of infection.

Try to limit the length of your stay on the field so that people do not accumulate in the place, but rather take turns.

We recommend that both child and you thoroughly disinfect their hands after visiting the playground.

5s.title: Visits to social facilities
5s.content:
Rules and recommendations

Visiting clients of elderly homes and "special care" facilities (in Czech: "domov se zvláštním režimem", facilities which provide stationary care for persons with reduced self-sufficiency, e.g. due to drug addiction or a mental illness) as well as of a respite care facility of any type is allowed, visitors must, however, have fulfilled one of the following requirements beforehand:

  • to undergo an AOC SARS-CoV-2 antigen test directly on the spot, i.e. in the facility where the client they want to visit resides, provided a negative result, or
  • not earlier than 48 hours before the visit, to undergo a RT-PCR SARS-CoV-2 presence test and to prove its negative result, or
  • to prove that they survived the SARS-CoV-2 infection personally (max. 90 days before the visit). 

During the entire visit, it is necessary to follow any and all internal operational measures of the facility.

Visitors have to leave their personal protective equipment put on during the entire visit. Note that a face mask is NOT considered sufficient - in the context given, at least a FFP2/KN95 respirator without an exhalation valve counts as such.

Remember, when planning such a visit you are going to enter a facility with a higher amount of people being prone to worse progress of the COVID-19 disease.
 

Please behave considerately during your visit.

5t.title: Children's contact with their friends
5t.content:
Rules and recommendations

The free movement of people is not restricted for the moment. It is important to consider the risk of each contact with other people. It is vital to abide by all the hygiene rules and recommendations.

Although, online platforms do not replace personal contact a meeting is not recommended. When a meeting is necessary, choose outdoor areas and wear a face mask. You can find out more about meetings and relevant current measures in section Meetings, parties, family celebrations.

Try to meet with your friends online. Help your kids to organize a phone call, play an online game together, or have a text conversation with their friends.

The current situation represents a huge strain on the mental health of all of us. Children perceive this stress very strongly as well as adults. Especially, if they are separated from their friends, grandparents and detached from the school or other environment. If your child is suffering from mental health problems due to isolation, fear of illness or stress from current state, we recommend reviewing the Stress and Pandemic Impact Management.

Try to meet with your friends online. Help your kids to organize a phone call, play an online game together, or have a text conversation with their friends.

The current situation represents a huge strain on the mental health of all of us. Children perceive this stress very strongly as well as adults. Especially, if they are separated from their friends, grandparents and detached from the school or other environment. If your child is suffering from mental health problems due to isolation, fear of illness, or stress from the current state, we recommend reviewing the Stress and Pandemic Impact Management.

5u.title: Divorced families
5u.content:
Rules and recommendations

The child has the right to see both parents even during a state of emergency. There is currently no restriction on the free movement of people.

From a legal point of view, therefore, there is no reason not to comply with the court's decision concerning children.

On the other hand, it is necessary to consider all the risks and try to create rules that reduce the possibility of disease transmission. Especially if the risk of infection is higher for one of the parents (such as health professionals or other people who are in contact with the sick or more people). However, such adjustments to the regime should be based on the agreement of both parents.

We recommend maintaining contact with the child through telephone calls, video calls, and other tools that allow at least alternative contact if quarantine or other measures do not allow personal contact.

A change in alternating care is also strongly recommended in case when one of the parents finds themself in isolation or quarantine. In this case, the transfer of the child should not take place. If the child is in the care of a parent who has to start quarantine for some reason, the child should remain in quarantine with that parent. If, on the other hand, the child is currently in the care of one parent and should transfer to a parent who has to start or is in quarantine as part of alternating care, we recommend that this transfer not take place.

5v.title: Dealing with official matters
5v.content:
Rules and recommendations

Office hours are limited to 2 days a week for 5 hours. You can find the opening hours for each Office on the official board of the given office, which is placed by the office building entrance.

Written and/or telephone contact is preferable over a personal visit to the office. This will help reduce the risk of infection to you and those around you.

You can also set up a data-box free of charge for online communication with the authorities. The data-box can be set up at any CzechPoint branch. If you have an e-ID (eObčanka), you can set up a data box online.

Only necessary matters should be handled in person. If you go to the office in person, it is necessary to have a facemask at all times, disinfect your hands and keep your distance. Keep a distance not only when in the queue but also when communicating with the officials.

If you need to stay at home with your child, fill out the application form for nursing. If you need more information about compensation within the nursing home, you can find it in Caregiver's allowance for self-employed II or Caregiver's allowance for full-time employees section.

If you are the recipient of housing allowance, child allowance or you have an increased care allowance of CZK 2,000, an extraordinary measure applies to you. Therefore, you do not have to document anything and submit to the Labor Office of the Czech Republic income or paid costs for housing for the months of July, August, September. You will receive the same amount automatically for the months of October, November, and December.

5w.title: Child's illness
5w.content:
Recommendation

If your child develops Covide-19 symptoms, contact your pediatrician.

In most cases, children are asymptomatic or have a very mild course of the disease. Your child's general practitioner will advise you on how to alleviate any symptoms of coronavirus.

Make sure the baby rests and drinks plenty of fluids. Continue the rest of the treatment and alleviate the symptoms as instructed by your doctor.

One of the first symptoms in children may be the so-called "covid fingers", which are red and swollen. Read more here.

Wait for the instructions of the Regional Hygiene Station and continue according to its instructions.

If a member of the household, in this case, a child, is quarantined, others need to be isolated. More information on this situation can be found in the A household member is positive section.

If your situation allows, place the child who has been infected in a separate room. This will reduce the risk of the disease spreading to your home.

  • Treat the infected person with mouth and nose protection.
  • Wash your hands and laundry often.
  • Contact limit.
  • Dine in a separate area.
  • Try not to use the same objects.
  • Monitor your health.

5x.title: Child birth
5x.content:
Rules and recommendations

The birth of a child is always a joyful occasion. However, it is important to follow strict hygiene rules. This way you will prevent the infection from spreading to the hospital environment. It is crucial to protect not just patients, but also the medical staff.

The participation of a third party in childbirth is permitted if the conditions are met:

  • The third party is the child's second parent or a person living with the mother in the same household.
  • The birth will take place in a separate delivery room or delivery area with its own bathroom.
  • Contact of the third party with other mothers will be prevented.
  • The third person undergoes temperature measurement before entering the delivery room or delivery area.
  • The third person has a body temperature of less than 37.0 ° C and at the same time has no COVID-19 symptoms.
  • The third party uses a surgical face mask as minimum respiratory protection (Non-surgical and fabric drapes or scarves are not enough !!)

We understand that for mothers, childbirth is very stressful and the presence of a close person can be helpful. However, this is possible under strict restrictions only. If you still suffer from stress, anxiety, or any psychological problems, you can read the Stress and handling impacts of the pandemic section.

5y.title: Sporting events
5y.content:
Rules and recommendations 

At the moment, professional and amateur competitions are allowed without public access. 

For professional athletes and the team around them, it is mandatory to test players before each event. Fan participation is prohibited. 

Professional athletes are allowed to play sports (training) to prepare for future events at indoor and outdoor sports grounds in unlimited numbers. However, they are subject to a strict obligation to observe all applicable hygienic conditions - social distancing and hand sanitation. Athletes do not have to wear a mask during the sport itself, but after training, it is necessary to put a mask on again under the regulations.

A professional athlete is a person who performs sport as his or her job or as a business or other similar activity.

5z.title: Castles and palaces
5z.content:
Rules and recommendations

Castles and chateaux may be open. However, the visitors group size is limited to 10 persons.

All hygiene measures remain in force (wearing masks, hands sanitizing and keeping the safety distance).

6a.title: Wearing masks is bad for your health
6a.content:
Hoax:

Different variations of the statement: “Face masks are bad for your immune system. Bacteria multiply in face masks. Face masks cause diseases. The WHO did not initially recommend the use of face masks. "

Explanation:

There is currently no evidence that wearing face masks weakens the immune system in any way. It is also nonsense that CO2 would accumulate under the face mask and harm us. The CO2 molecules are so small that it is no problem for them to go through the mask. Only bacteria that you exhale yourself will stay inside the mask. If you use it properly and wash or boil it after each use, there can be no significant multiplication of bacteria.

Nor is there any evidence that the masks can cause any diseases. The only possible health problem caused by wearing a mask may be an allergic reaction of the skin to the material from which the face mask is made (if you suffer from such an allergy).

Yes, the WHO did not recommend the use of face masks in the first wave. But it was not because it was ineffective, but for fear of misuse. When used and worn properly, face masks are an effective protection against  the sprea of coronavirus according to the WHO.

Here is an explanation of the whole hoax (in Czech)

or here.

6b.title: Recommendations for landlords
6b.content:
